const tristanBaiaContent = `<h2>Interview with Tristan Baia</h2><br>
<p><strong>Nom de l'artiste / Nom de la publication:</strong> Tristan Baia</p><br>
<p><strong>What sparked your interest in creating zines?</strong></p><br>
<p>I encountered zines at around two points - first, I learned about zines from various queer groups and individuals on social media sites on tumblr, but more from a theoretical sense. My first encounter with actual/tangible zines was during my undergraduate Fine Art degree at Wits University, which is what really got me interested in the medium. I've always been very interested in paper works and print media (especially indie/queer print media) and these little booklets felt very accessible and interesting to me. They've become a very important part of my creative practice, to the point where they became the focus of my recent masters in contemporary curatorial practice - in navigating how the accessible and decentralised nature of zines and zining might enable an affective/queer(ed) curatorial practice.</p>
<p><strong>Could you walk me through your creative and material process when making zines? (how do you brainstorm your content / any media that you experiment with or prefer to use)</strong></p>
<p>My creative process for zines involves a substantial amount of collage work, using both my own photography as well as scanned text and images (I'm trying to get more into hand drawn zines atm tho). Additionally, my zines often emerge in response to something. For example, my zine "ANDROGEN" was in response to reading Anne Fausto-Sterling's book "Sexing the Body" and seeking some way to grapple with and express the content of her writing. My zine "BEEF" emerged as a tangible result of my research into the archiving of gay pornographic magazines, and the subsequent challenges in access, intention, and preservation of these magazines. As such, both of these zines feature heavy usage of appropriated text and images respectively from the source media that I am attempting to work with, which I then distort, collage, or remake throughout the zine. However, I am currently in a very experimental stage with zines, and just having fun creating them off the cuff and seeing what emerges.</p><br>
<p><strong>How do you share your zines with others?</strong></p>
<p>I mainly hand distribute/trade zines with interested parties! I don't really sell my zines at the moment, and I prefer the face-to-face tactility of trading zines over digital distribution methods.</p><br>
<p><strong>Have you faced any interesting challenges or successes while getting your zines out there?</strong></p>
<p>One issue I find is people simply not knowing what they are - however, I've also found that people are very receptive to the format once it is introduced to them. That said, my largest issue is primarily related to community - not knowing many zinesters in South Africa often means that I lack individuals to trade or distribute zines with outside of my already established circles.</p><br>
<p><strong>Do you actively participate in any specific zine-making communities or networks?</strong></p>
<p>Unfortunately not - I'm not the most social person, so I'm not really aware of any zining networks within South Africa. I more so tend to trade with individuals that I know/meet that are into zines and zining.</p><br>
<p><strong>Have you ever teamed up with other artists or zine makers? If so, how did those collaborations come about?</strong></p>
<p>Only once! I produced a joint zine back in university as a submission for an assignment, but I'd love to do another collaboration at some point without those institution hanging over me.</p><br>
<p><strong>How much value do you place on the sense of community within the zine-making scene?</strong></p>
<p>For me, it's one of the most valuable aspects of zines. I feel like each time you trade/sell a zine, you make a new connection, so in that sense zines are great for fostering/supporting communal connections (I write about this in my research). It's also much harder to engage in a kind of zining practice without those communal connections (speaking from experience here).</p><br>
<p><strong>Have you ever taken part in zine fairs, workshops, or similar events? If so, how did they impact your creative process / engagement with the community?</strong></p>
<p>I haven't taken part in any zine fairs or events - however, as part of my own master's research I coordinated a zine jam workshop, which was quite a fun experience. The majority of the individuals for the workshop had never made a zine before, so it was nice being able to introduce new people to zines and see how they approached the format in their own unique ways. I also recently held another zine making workshop for a group of students.</p><br>
<p><strong>When it comes to preserving your zines, what's your approach?</strong></p>
<p>I'm in two minds about preservation. I feel that part of what makes zines so interesting is their ephemerality, in that they are inherently fragile paper works that demand a tactile engagement with them, and tactile engagements are often anti-archival. So while I do try to preserve my zines (both my own and those that I've collected) as part of maintaining my own little zine library, I'm not so worried about preservation that I stop people from touching them - rather I encourage people to touch and read them, as I feel this is important to their core materiality, even if this compromises archival integrity. Simultaneously, I don't use any digital preservation methods, as I feel like this also robs zines of their tactility. I guess my response to preserving zines comes down to this - zines are created to be touched, held, folded, and read, and if this leads to damage, so be it, because at least it was used for its original purpose. I create zines to be read, not to be stared at longingly.</p><br>
<p><strong>Do you think about how future generations might access your work? If so, in what ways?</strong></p>
<p>I'll be entirely honest, this isn't something I've ever thought of before. I'm not sure if it's something that particularly concerns me - I'm more interested in the immediacy of zines as a format.</p><br>
<p><strong>Have you faced any interesting challenges or considerations regarding the archiving of your zines?</strong></p>
<p>Not particularly - I store them in an archival folder. I suppose my biggest issue with archiving my zines is how to share them - I'm always concerned that I may not get them back when I share them with large groups.</p><br>
<p><strong>What are your thoughts on the idea of zines being part of public library collections?</strong></p>
<p>I'm very for the idea! I think it would be a great way to introduce more people to the format, and I also think that zines often hold a wealth of great information written by people who may not have the means to publish a book - their format should not disqualify their value as sources of information. Especially since zines are often used as tools for disseminating counterculture/radical/subversive info - including them in public libraries consequently increases the amount of information people have access to. However, I feel like their inclusion into these spaces should be up to the decision of the original author - zines can sometimes contain very sensitive or personal information, and the original author might have never intended for them to be disseminated outside of particular circles (see QZAP's politics on collection/archiving of zines).</p><br>
<p><strong>In your view, what role do zines play in today's culture?</strong></p>
<p>As social media has become much more prevalent, our ability to share things with wide audiences has widely increased - however, I also feel like this comes with a loss of control. I feel like with zines, you can somewhat control the flow of your information, either by printing a smaller edition, or deciding who you want to share your information with - there's a sort of exclusivity or intimacy that I feel social media is currently lacking. Unfortunately, they aren't that prevalent outside of very specific artistic/zining communities, so I don't know if I would say they play much of a role in contemporary culture in the same way that they did in the pre-social media and the internet. I would love it if they did become more prevalent though.</p><br>
<p><strong>How do you believe zines contribute to discussions about identity, politics, or social issues?</strong></p>
<p>I really feel like zines are one of the best formats when talking about identity/politics/social media. Because they are self-published and produced, they are not beholden to institutional limitations or constraints on their contents, which means they are often able to speak on issues that social media sites/newspapers/other media platforms might otherwise choose not to discuss. Here, I think about the established trans communities in the UK that are currently using zines as a tool to disseminate information on trans-centric healthcare practices (see Nat Raha's essay "Trans Healthcare in Zines").</p><br>
<p><strong>Have you received any memorable reactions or impacts from your zine creations within your audience or community?</strong></p>
<p>I've gotten a few really pleasant reactions from sharing my zines, but what I find really gratifying is sharing the format as a whole with new people. There's something really cool about hosting a workshop and seeing someone's eyes light up like "oh, I can fill this with anything I want". I still treasure the zines created by the participants in my first workshop.</p><br>
<p><strong>What do you find most challenging and rewarding about the zine-making process?</strong></p>
<p>The process of bringing it all together, there's something so cool about having all these ideas in your head and suddenly having this very real little booklet in your hand that you can flip through, it's like oh my gosh, I made this.</p><br>
<p><strong>Where do you envision zine making, distribution, and archiving heading in the future?</strong></p>
<p>Everything is becoming more digital/online-centric nowadays, and I certainly see the same thing happening to zines, which makes me a bit sad. I definitely feel like digizines have their place, but nothing will ever beat the tactility of a paper zine for me.</p><br>
<p><strong>Are there any changes or developments within the zine-making community that you're excited about or hope to see?</strong></p>
<p>I hope to see more people start to use zines in their practices! I've been teaching people how to make zines recently, and I would be very happy to know if even a few of those people continued to use zines to express themselves artistically/politically/etc. I want more people to make zines, because I love reading zines and learning new things!</p><br>
<p><strong>What are your favourite zines?</strong></p>
<p>I really enjoy reading zines created by newcomers to the zine scene. There's something very fresh and exciting about reading a zine created by someone who is still figuring out what the format can offer. That said, I'm not sure if I have a particularly favourite genre or style. I just think zines are neat :)</p>`;

